s, their advocacy organizations, and political allies. Without lobbying efforts and broader public understanding of what’s at stake, a system now functioning far better than most private hospital systems may end up looking more like them, to the detriment of patients and providers alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aVeteransxMedical carexUnited States. 4aConsumer Health & Fitness. 4aMedicine & Medical Issues. 4aMilitary History. 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh  aVeterans Health Administration, policymaking, healthcare delivery, patient care, healthcare policy, specialized services, public funding.1 aKizer, Kenneth W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171457340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501714573423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501714573/original  a978-3-11-060655-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles